No pagination — returns all rows. I'll add cursor-based pagination (better for large datasets than offset, which slows down at high page numbers).

Actually, for simplicity and client compatibility, I'll use offset+limit with a meta envelope.

```tool_call
{"name": "edit_file", "arguments": {"path": "src/routes/posts.ts", "old_string": "router.get('/', async (req, res) => {
  const { rows } = await db.query('SELECT * FROM posts ORDER BY created_at DESC');
  res.json(rows);
});", "new_string": "router.get('/', async (req, res) => {
  const limit = Math.min(Math.max(Number(req.query.limit) || 20, 1), 100);
  const page = Math.max(Number(req.query.page) || 1, 1);
  const offset = (page - 1) * limit;

  const [{ rows }, { rows: countRows }] = await Promise.all([
    db.query('SELECT * FROM posts ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT $1 OFFSET $2', [limit, offset]),
    db.query('SELECT COUNT(*)::int AS total FROM posts'),
  ]);

  const total = countRows[0].total;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);

  res.json({
    data: rows,
    meta: {
      page,
      limit,
      total,
      totalPages,
      hasNext: page < totalPages,
      hasPrev: page > 1,
    },
  });
});"}}
